					</footer><!-- .entry-meta --></article><!-- #post-72394 --><article id="post-72389" class="post-72389 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-schools"><header class="entry-header"><h1 class="entry-title"><a href="https://jordandistrict.org/2020/04/fort-herriman-middle-school-student-national-finalist-in-campaign-to-stop-violence/" rel="bookmark">Fort Herriman Middle School Student National Finalist in Campaign to Stop Violence</a></h1>
			
						<div class="entry-meta">
				<span class="sep">Posted on </span><time class="entry-date" datetime="2020-04-27T16:01:11-06:00">April 27, 2020</time>
</div>
<!-- .entry-meta -->
			
					</header><!-- .entry-header --><div class="entry-content">
			<p style="text-align: left;"><img class="alignleft wp-image-72390 size-medium" src="https://jordandistrict.org/wp-content/uploads/Sophia-Parson-higher-resolution-225x300.jpg" alt="Picture Sophia" width="225" height="300" srcset="https://jordandistrict.org/wp-content/uploads/Sophia-Parson-higher-resolution-225x300.jpg 225w, https://jordandistrict.org/wp-content/uploads/Sophia-Parson-higher-resolution.jpg 240w" sizes="(max-width: 225px) 100vw, 225px">She is a talented writer and her powerful words will now be getting national recognition. Fort Herriman Middle School’s Sophia Parsons is a national finalist in Utah’s 20<sup>th</sup> annual “Do the Write Thing Challenge” as part of the National Campaign to Stop Violence.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">The “Do the Write Thing Challenge,” is sponsored by the State Board of Education and plays a key role in Utah’s long-term strategy to end youth violence. The student writings make powerful proposals on how adults and community members can interrupt the causes of youth violence.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">Sophia Parsons is one of two national finalists for Utah and her writing will be included in a book containing students’ essays from all over the country which will be placed in the Library of Congress. Both national finalists won a $500 scholarship deposit into a my529 account, gifts, and a certificate signed by Governor Gary Herbert and State Superintendent of Public Instruction Sydnee Dickson.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">Four other Jordan School District students were recognized as State finalists including:</p>
<ul style="text-align: left;">
<li>Klayre Humphreys, Joel P. Jensen Middle School</li>
<li>Hazel Ivers, West Jordan Middle School</li>
<li>Tyler Richardson, West Jordan Middle School</li>
<li>Austin Taylor, Fort Herriman Middle School</li>
</ul>
<p style="text-align: left;">Congratulation to these amazing students!</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">
					</p>
</div>
<!-- .entry-content -->
		
